{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MTjRKP2W1Lzc79mKatzjeg","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Issue #895: Check quantile prediction order helper function\n     2→\n     3→## Source\n     4→\n     5→- **GitHub**: https://github.com/epiforecasts/scoringutils/issues/895\n     6→- **Related**: https://github.com/epiforecasts/scoringutils/issues/412\n     7→- **Action Summary**: Create a user-facing helper (e.g., `get_non_monotonic_forecasts()`) to identify rows where predictions decrease with increasing quantile level, and add a warning in `assert_forecast.forecast_quantile()`. Resolves both #895 and #412.\n     8→- **Status Note**: Monotonicity check only exists deep in `bias_quantile_single_vector()` (metrics-quantile.R:495) as a hard error. No early warning in `assert_forecast.forecast_quantile()`. No user-facing diagnostic function. Issue #412 is the maintainer-created parent with an agreed plan (steps 1 and 3 not done).\n     9→\n    10→## Test Specifications\n    11→\n    12→**Designed**: 2026-02-13\n    13→**Test files**: `tests/testthat/test-class-forecast-quantile.R` (existing) and `tests/testthat/test-get-duplicate-forecasts.R` (existing, to add sibling tests for `get_non_monotonic_forecasts()`)\n    14→**Testing patterns observed**: testthat with data.table fixtures; `example_quantile` dataset used extensively; `expect_no_condition()` for passing cases, `expect_error()`/`expect_warning()` for failing cases; `suppressMessages(suppressWarnings(...))` around `as_forecast_quantile()` calls; setup.R pre-computes `scores_quantile` and `metrics_no_cov`; no helper-*.R files exist\n    15→\n    16→## Implementation Context\n    17→\n    18→The fix has three parts:\n    19→1. **New function `get_non_monotonic_forecasts()`** — user-facing diagnostic, modeled on `get_duplicate_forecasts()` (in `R/get-duplicate-forecasts.R`). Takes a forecast object (or data with `quantile_level` and `predicted` columns), groups by forecast unit, orders by `quantile_level` within each group, and returns rows where `predicted` decreases as `quantile_level` increases.\n    20→2. **Warning in `assert_forecast.forecast_quantile()`** — after the existing 4 checks (line 84-87 of `R/class-forecast-quantile.R`), add a call that detects non-monotonic forecasts and emits `cli_warn()` (not `cli_abort()`), guarded by `verbose`.\n    21→3. **Internal helper `check_monotonicity()`** — analogous to `check_duplicates()`, calls `get_non_monotonic_forecasts()` and returns `TRUE` or an error message string. Used by `assert_forecast.forecast_quantile()`.\n    22→\n    23→---\n    24→\n    25→### Test 1: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() returns empty data.table for well-formed quantile forecasts\", { ... })\n    26→\n    27→**Reproduces**: baseline correctness — well-formed data should produce no results\n    28→**File**: `tests/testthat/test-class-forecast-quantile.R` (or a new `test-get-non-monotonic-forecasts.R` following the `test-get-duplicate-forecasts.R` naming pattern)\n    29→**Setup**:\n    30→- Use `example_quantile` directly (built-in dataset with well-formed quantile forecasts)\n    31→**Action**:\n    32→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(example_quantile)`\n    33→**Expected**:\n    34→- `expect_identical(nrow(get_non_monotonic_forecasts(example_quantile)), 0L)` — no rows returned\n    35→- Result should be a `data.table`\n    36→**Fails now because**:\n    37→- Function `get_non_monotonic_forecasts()` does not exist yet; call will error with \"could not find function\"\n    38→\n    39→---\n    40→\n    41→### Test 2: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() detects predictions that decrease with increasing quantile level\", { ... })\n    42→\n    43→**Reproduces**: the core bug — non-monotonic predictions are not flagged until deep inside `bias_quantile()`\n    44→**File**: same as Test 1\n    45→**Setup**:\n    46→- Create a minimal quantile forecast data.table with one forecast unit having non-monotonic predictions:\n    47→  ```\n    48→  data.table(\n    49→    model = \"model1\",\n    50→    date = as.Date(\"2020-01-01\"),\n    51→    observed = 5,\n    52→    quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75),\n    53→    predicted = c(3, 7, 4)    # 7 > 4 violates monotonicity at q=0.75\n    54→  )\n    55→  ```\n    56→- Convert to `forecast_quantile` using `suppressWarnings(suppressMessages(as_forecast_quantile(...)))`\n    57→**Action**:\n    58→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(data)` on the constructed data\n    59→**Expected**:\n    60→- Result has `nrow > 0` — the non-monotonic forecast unit is returned\n    61→- The returned rows should contain the forecast unit where the violation occurs (model=\"model1\", date=\"2020-01-01\")\n    62→- All quantile rows for that forecast unit should be included (so the user can see the full picture), i.e., `nrow(result) == 3`\n    63→**Fails now because**:\n    64→- Function does not exist yet\n    65→\n    66→---\n    67→\n    68→### Test 3: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() handles multiple forecast units with mixed monotonicity\", { ... })\n    69→\n    70→**Reproduces**: edge case — only some forecast units are non-monotonic; function should return only the bad ones\n    71→**File**: same as Test 1\n    72→**Setup**:\n    73→- Create a data.table with two forecast units:\n    74→  - Unit A (model=\"good_model\", date=\"2020-01-01\"): `quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75)`, `predicted = c(2, 5, 8)` — monotonic, well-formed\n    75→  - Unit B (model=\"bad_model\", date=\"2020-01-01\"): `quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75)`, `predicted = c(3, 7, 4)` — non-monotonic\n    76→  - Both have `observed = 5`\n    77→- Convert to `forecast_quantile`\n    78→**Action**:\n    79→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(data)`\n    80→**Expected**:\n    81→- Only rows for \"bad_model\" are returned\n    82→- Rows for \"good_model\" are NOT included\n    83→- `nrow(result) == 3` (all 3 quantile rows for the bad forecast unit)\n    84→**Fails now because**:\n    85→- Function does not exist yet\n    86→\n    87→---\n    88→\n    89→### Test 4: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() works with counts argument\", { ... })\n    90→\n    91→**Reproduces**: the `counts` parameter pattern from `get_duplicate_forecasts()`\n    92→**File**: same as Test 1\n    93→**Setup**:\n    94→- Create a data.table with 2 forecast units that are non-monotonic and 1 that is monotonic:\n    95→  - Unit A (model=\"bad1\", date=\"2020-01-01\"): non-monotonic predictions\n    96→  - Unit B (model=\"bad2\", date=\"2020-01-01\"): non-monotonic predictions\n    97→  - Unit C (model=\"good\", date=\"2020-01-01\"): monotonic predictions\n    98→  - All with `quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75)`, `observed = 5`\n    99→- Convert to `forecast_quantile`\n   100→**Action**:\n   101→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(data, counts = TRUE)`\n   102→**Expected**:\n   103→- Returns a summary data.table with one row per non-monotonic forecast unit\n   104→- `nrow(result) == 2` (for bad1 and bad2)\n   105→- Contains a count column (e.g., `n_non_monotonic`) indicating the number of quantile rows per affected forecast unit\n   106→**Fails now because**:\n   107→- Function does not exist yet\n   108→\n   109→---\n   110→\n   111→### Test 5: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() accepts custom forecast_unit argument\", { ... })\n   112→\n   113→**Reproduces**: the `forecast_unit` parameter pattern from `get_duplicate_forecasts()`\n   114→**File**: same as Test 1\n   115→**Setup**:\n   116→- Use `example_quantile` or a crafted dataset with extra columns\n   117→- A custom `forecast_unit` specification that differs from the default\n   118→**Action**:\n   119→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(data, forecast_unit = c(\"location\", \"target_end_date\", \"target_type\", \"model\"))`\n   120→**Expected**:\n   121→- `expect_no_condition(get_non_monotonic_forecasts(example_quantile, forecast_unit = c(\"location\", \"target_end_date\", \"target_type\", \"location_name\", \"forecast_date\", \"model\")))` succeeds\n   122→- Returns 0 rows for the well-formed `example_quantile`\n   123→**Fails now because**:\n   124→- Function does not exist yet\n   125→\n   126→---\n   127→\n   128→### Test 6: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() returns expected class\", { ... })\n   129→\n   130→**Reproduces**: output type contract\n   131→**File**: same as Test 1\n   132→**Setup**:\n   133→- Use `example_quantile`\n   134→**Action**:\n   135→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(example_quantile)`\n   136→**Expected**:\n   137→- `expect_s3_class(result, c(\"data.table\", \"data.frame\"))` — matches the pattern from `get_duplicate_forecasts()`\n   138→**Fails now because**:\n   139→- Function does not exist yet\n   140→\n   141→---\n   142→\n   143→### Test 7: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() works with a plain data.frame input\", { ... })\n   144→\n   145→**Reproduces**: data.frame compatibility (matches `get_duplicate_forecasts()` test pattern)\n   146→**File**: same as Test 1\n   147→**Setup**:\n   148→- Create a data.frame (not data.table) with non-monotonic quantile predictions:\n   149→  ```\n   150→  data.frame(\n   151→    model = \"model1\",\n   152→    date = as.Date(\"2020-01-01\"),\n   153→    observed = 5,\n   154→    quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75),\n   155→    predicted = c(3, 7, 4)\n   156→  )\n   157→  ```\n   158→**Action**:\n   159→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(df_input)`\n   160→**Expected**:\n   161→- Returns rows identifying the non-monotonic forecast (same as data.table input)\n   162→- Output is a `data.table`/`data.frame`\n   163→**Fails now because**:\n   164→- Function does not exist yet\n   165→\n   166→---\n   167→\n   168→### Test 8: test_that(\"assert_forecast.forecast_quantile() warns about non-monotonic predictions\", { ... })\n   169→\n   170→**Reproduces**: the core issue — non-monotonic predictions silently pass `assert_forecast()` until they hit `bias_quantile()` deep in `score()`\n   171→**File**: `tests/testthat/test-class-forecast-quantile.R` (existing)\n   172→**Setup**:\n   173→- Create a data.table with non-monotonic predictions:\n   174→  ```\n   175→  data.table(\n   176→    model = \"model1\",\n   177→    date = as.Date(\"2020-01-01\"),\n   178→    observed = 5,\n   179→    quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75),\n   180→    predicted = c(3, 7, 4)\n   181→  )\n   182→  ```\n   183→**Action**:\n   184→- Call `as_forecast_quantile(data)` which internally calls `assert_forecast.forecast_quantile()`\n   185→**Expected**:\n   186→- `expect_warning(as_forecast_quantile(data), \"non-monotonic|decreasing|predictions must not be decreasing\")` — a warning (not error) is emitted mentioning non-monotonic predictions\n   187→- The function should still succeed (return a valid `forecast_quantile` object), just with a warning\n   188→- The warning message should mention `get_non_monotonic_forecasts()` so users know how to diagnose\n   189→**Fails now because**:\n   190→- Current `assert_forecast.forecast_quantile()` (lines 81-89 of `R/class-forecast-quantile.R`) has no monotonicity check at all. Non-monotonic data passes silently through `as_forecast_quantile()` and only errors later inside `bias_quantile_single_vector()` at scoring time.\n   191→\n   192→---\n   193→\n   194→### Test 9: test_that(\"assert_forecast.forecast_quantile() does not warn for well-formed data\", { ... })\n   195→\n   196→**Reproduces**: regression guard — well-formed data should not trigger the new warning\n   197→**File**: `tests/testthat/test-class-forecast-quantile.R` (existing)\n   198→**Setup**:\n   199→- Use `na.omit(data.table::copy(example_quantile))` (known well-formed data)\n   200→**Action**:\n   201→- Call `as_forecast_quantile(data)`\n   202→**Expected**:\n   203→- `expect_no_condition(as_forecast_quantile(data))` — no warnings or messages emitted\n   204→- This is already partially tested by the existing test at line 19-29 of `test-class-forecast-quantile.R`, but should be explicitly confirmed in the context of the new monotonicity check\n   205→**Fails now because**:\n   206→- This test should PASS both before and after the fix. It guards against false positives.\n   207→\n   208→---\n   209→\n   210→### Test 10: test_that(\"assert_forecast.forecast_quantile() suppresses monotonicity warning when verbose = FALSE\", { ... })\n   211→\n   212→**Reproduces**: the `verbose` parameter behavior — user should be able to suppress the warning\n   213→**File**: `tests/testthat/test-class-forecast-quantile.R` (existing)\n   214→**Setup**:\n   215→- Create the same non-monotonic data as Test 8\n   216→- First convert to `forecast_quantile` (suppressing the warning)\n   217→**Action**:\n   218→- Call `assert_forecast(forecast_obj, verbose = FALSE)` on the non-monotonic forecast object\n   219→**Expected**:\n   220→- `expect_no_condition(assert_forecast(forecast_obj, verbose = FALSE))` — no warning emitted when verbose is FALSE\n   221→**Fails now because**:\n   222→- No monotonicity check exists yet; `verbose` parameter has no effect on non-existent check\n   223→\n   224→---\n   225→\n   226→### Test 11: test_that(\"score() works end-to-end with non-monotonic predictions after fix, excluding bias\", { ... })\n   227→\n   228→**Reproduces**: the user's pain point — `score()` fails entirely because `bias_quantile()` errors on non-monotonic predictions, preventing all other metrics from being computed\n   229→**File**: `tests/testthat/test-class-forecast-quantile.R` (existing)\n   230→**Setup**:\n   231→- Create a forecast with non-monotonic predictions in one forecast unit (same data as Test 2)\n   232→- Convert to `forecast_quantile` (suppressing the new warning)\n   233→**Action**:\n   234→- Call `score(data, metrics = list(wis = wis))` — a metric that does NOT require monotonicity\n   235→**Expected**:\n   236→- After the fix, `score()` with non-bias metrics should succeed (WIS does not require monotonicity)\n   237→- `bias_quantile` should still error (or warn) when called individually on non-monotonic data\n   238→- This test verifies that `score()` overall is not broken by non-monotonic data when bias is excluded\n   239→**Fails now because**:\n   240→- Currently `score()` will error with \"Predictions must not be decreasing\" because `bias_quantile` is in the default metrics and its error propagation via `run_safely()` converts to a warning. However, the WIS metric itself does not require monotonicity and should compute fine. The core issue is that the user gets no early warning during `as_forecast_quantile()` — they only discover the problem at `score()` time.\n   241→\n   242→---\n   243→\n   244→### Test 12: test_that(\"get_non_monotonic_forecasts() handles equal predictions at adjacent quantile levels\", { ... })\n   245→\n   246→**Reproduces**: edge case — equal predictions at different quantile levels (flat segments) should NOT be flagged as non-monotonic; only strictly decreasing values are violations\n   247→**File**: same as Test 1\n   248→**Setup**:\n   249→- Create data with flat predictions:\n   250→  ```\n   251→  data.table(\n   252→    model = \"model1\",\n   253→    date = as.Date(\"2020-01-01\"),\n   254→    observed = 5,\n   255→    quantile_level = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75),\n   256→    predicted = c(3, 5, 5)    # 5 == 5 is OK (non-decreasing)\n   257→  )\n   258→  ```\n   259→- Convert to `forecast_quantile`\n   260→**Action**:\n   261→- Call `get_non_monotonic_forecasts(data)`\n   262→**Expected**:\n   263→- `expect_identical(nrow(result), 0L)` — flat segments are valid (non-decreasing is the requirement, matching `diff(predicted) >= 0` in the existing `bias_quantile` check)\n   264→**Fails now because**:\n   265→- Function does not exist yet\n   266→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015Nto4GSrTWw9Rbezap7U8c","session_id":"18263a2a-ff1c-4bcf-92eb-332cab9cfb17","uuid":"8c8341ea-fd81-4523-b70f-9eed83c338b0"}
